Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new members to the board of the US central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious question to ask first is how it was possible for the Fed to miss its most important mandate – ensuring price stability – to such an extent.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Now, institutional self-examination is undoubtedly appropriate.
Yet while monetary policy is making headlines, the Fed is now mainly significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether it will use its enormous power to advance climate or social policy.
For example, the Fed could refuse to grant loans to companies in the fossil fuel sector, it could require banks to grant loans only to companies with certified net-zero emission plans, or it could direct lending toward desired alternatives.
Moreover, it could decide to explicitly take on regulatory activities in the name of equality or ethnic justice by requiring banks to specify where and to whom loans are granted, who is hired and who is fired, and so on.
Yet before we turn to the question of in which direction the Fed's regulation will or should move, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's serious failure.
In 2008, the US government made a fateful decision: financial institutions could still predominantly finance risky investments by selling short-term, run-prone debt instruments, but armies of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the risk exposure of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large chunks of subprime mortgage debt in bank balance sheets.
Yet in the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once asked what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually occurred in early 2020, the Fed discarded its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened even more extensively.
In March, the commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for plain vanilla US government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The corrections in the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been postponed.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed again rescued the money market funds.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but this never happened.
Moreover, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the rescue package for the financial industry - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
But in 2020, with the "Powell put" - among other things - an explicit lower bound for corporate bond prices was introduced.
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could certainly have triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the US Treasury will simply put out any new fire with a new flood of liquidity.
The problem, however, lies in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why bother to make the effort and use reserves or balance sheet space to provide liquidity or treat a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity" when prices are falling?
The Fed will anyway outpace everyone and pocket the profits.
Why would companies still issue shares when they can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state supports the debt or helps the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why would investors hesitate when it comes to buying dubious securities, when their value is guaranteed by another "Whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed in bad times?
No wonder America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will cover the losses during the next downturn.
Student loans, government pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
But each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put more money into rescue operations and people will not be happy with billions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up to a big fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulatory authorities and lawmakers at least still recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would have to cover the losses.
In 2020, however, people indulged themselves in complacency regarding the rescue operations.
Exactly the Fed, which failed to anticipate the risks of the subprime mortgages in 2008 as well as the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests with regard to "climate risks," will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators do not even ask the question about the mentioned events.
And although jargon about "interconnections," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define "systemic" risk at all, apart from the fact that it has become a catch-all term that grants regulatory authorities comprehensive power.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to predict risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that immense debts can always be paid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always bails out mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
Better regulation can bridge political divides.
The Left is right when it argues that large banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans little.
However, it is based on the wrong cause.
An immense cost for complying with regulations poses a major barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is senseless.
Regulatory provisions are either smart or stupid, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well designed.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to have prophetic abilities.
The Fed scandalously blocked companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sectors that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it commits itself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it fulfills its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
